        'The distinction is everything. Skill is something you have — a capacity you can describe, measure, demonstrate. Enskilment is something you\'re undergoing — a progressive deepening of embodied, embedded attentiveness to a domain. It cannot be separated from the context you\'re practicing in. It cannot be possessed in the abstract and deployed elsewhere. It grows in place, through the ongoing relationship between you and your field.',
        'Ingold wrote that enskilment is "a progressively deepening embodied-embedded attentiveness." Read that slowly. Progressively deepening. Not just deepening — progressively. There is no end state. There is only the ongoing process of becoming more attuned to a domain that keeps revealing more of itself as your attentiveness grows.',
        'The word "embedded" is doing important work in that definition. Embedded means situated — in a context, in a practice, in a history of engagement with something real. The enskilled practitioner is not someone who has extracted principles from their domain and stored them for portable use. They are someone who has been shaped by sustained engagement with a specific field in a specific way, and that shaping is inseparable from the engagement itself.',
