        'Knowledge-of is something else entirely. It\'s the knowledge you have when you\'re in the middle of doing something — the knowing that lives in the act itself, that cannot be extracted from the performance without losing what makes it knowing. A jazz musician\'s knowledge of how this particular chord resolves in this particular moment, given this particular room and this particular band and this particular tension that has been building for six bars. That knowledge doesn\'t translate to a proposition. It doesn\'t survive the extraction. It exists only in the playing.',
        'The philosopher Michael Polanyi called this "tacit knowledge" — knowledge we have but cannot fully articulate. He wrote: "We know more than we can tell." What he was pointing at is exactly this. The enskilled practitioner\'s knowledge is not mostly tacit because it\'s mysterious or ineffable. It\'s tacit because the knowing and the doing are the same thing. Separating them is not simplification — it\'s destruction.',
