        'What actually happens is this: long plateaus punctuated by rapid reorganizations.',
        'You work for weeks or months. Nothing seems to change. The metrics stay flat. The performances don\'t noticeably improve. You\'re doing the right things — the constraint work, the variable practice, the bottleneck focus — and the returns seem invisible. And then, sometimes almost overnight, something reorganizes. The skill snaps into a qualitatively different configuration. Not a little better — different. The landscape shifts. Things that were difficult become approachable. New things that were invisible become visible. You have phase-transitioned.',
        'In systems science, this is called a phase transition. Water doesn\'t gradually become ice — it\'s liquid until the temperature hits a critical threshold, and then it transforms. The transformation isn\'t gradual. The preparation is gradual. The transition is sudden. And you cannot predict exactly when the threshold will be crossed by watching the water — it looks the same at 35 degrees as it does at 33, but the behavior at 31 is completely different.',
        'Skill development works the same way. The plateau is not failure. The plateau is the preparation. You are building the conditions for a phase transition, and the transition will not announce itself in advance. It will come when the system has accumulated enough coherent pressure to reorganize — not when you feel ready, not when the calendar says it\'s time, not on any predictable schedule.',
        'The problem is that our entire cultural framework around effort and improvement is built on the assumption of linear return. Work harder, get better proportionally. And when you hit a plateau, the cultural narrative says something is wrong — you\'re not trying hard enough, or you\'re practicing the wrong thing, or you\'ve hit a natural ceiling.',
